<header>
	Complete the sentences by choosing the word or phrase which best fits each gap.
</header>
	
<section id="body">
  <img class="rightFloat" src="../media/SS_AW_015.jpg" mode="1" id="1001"/>
</section>

<section id="fb1">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">1. <b>would:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>will:</b> This is a hypothetical statement. The 'conditional' form of the verb is needed here.<b/></font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>should:</b> Another modal is needed here.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb2">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">2. <b>allowing:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>allowed:</b> The present participle is needed here.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>allows:</b> This is a kind of contracted relative clause using a participle verb form.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb3">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">3. <b>denied:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>denying:</b> The past participle is needed here.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>deny:</b> This is a kind of contracted relative clause using a participle verb form.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb4">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">4. <b>which:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>who:</b> The missing pronoun does not refer to a person.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>...:</b> The pronoun can only be omitted if it refers to the object of the verb in the relative clause.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb5">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">5. <b>likelihood:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb6">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">6. <b>have given rise to:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>are due to/stem from:</b> What follows the gap is the result, not the cause.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb7">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">7. <b>those:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>they:</b> You need a plural pronoun.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>these:</b> You need a pronoun which refers to something distant (on the other side of the world in this case).</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb8">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">8. <b>so that:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>because of:</b> What follows this gap is the result, not the cause.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>in order to:</b> This phrase needs to be followed with a verb in the infinitive.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb9">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">9. <b>whereas:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>consequently/furthermore:</b> What's missing is a connecting word which emphasises the contrast between these two facts.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb10">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">10. <b>opinion:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb11">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">11. <b>brought:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>bring/have brought:</b> What's needed here is the 'conditional' form of the verb, which shows that the statements are hypothetical. The form is 'would + past participle'.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb12">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">12. <b>where:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>that/which:</b> The missing pronoun refers to a place.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb13">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">13. <b>are due to:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>bring about/lead to:</b> What follows that gap is the cause, not the result.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb14">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">14. <b>who:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>that:</b> It is not possible to use the pronoun 'that' in a non-defining clause like this one.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>...:</b> It is not possible to omit the relative pronoun in a non-defining clause like this one.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb15">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">15. <b>In spite:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>Despite:</b> 'Despite' isn't followed by 'of'.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>Although:</b> 'Although' is followed by a verb clause, with subject and verb: 'Although the government have made efforts.'</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb16">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">16. <b>could well:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb17">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">17. <b>voting:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>voted:</b> The present participle is needed here.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>vote:</b> This would need a full relative clause: 'who vote'. Instead, a participle clause is used here.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb18">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">18. <b>such:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>example/like:</b> An example is being given here, but notice the word 'as' after the gap.</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb19">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">19. <b>unlikely:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>impossible:</b>  Intensifying adverbs such as 'very' or 'highly' can't be used with 'impossible'. Either something is impossible, or it isn't .</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb20">
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#0000ff">20. <b>However:</b> This is the correct answer.</font>
  </p>
  <p align="left">
    <font color="#000000"><b>Although/Whereas:</b> Notice that this is the beginning of a new sentence with only one main clause. 'Although' and 'Whereas' are used to join two clauses together, so they can't be used here.</font>
  </p>
</section>

